To identify CNPs that rise from germline mutation, we used focal CNV profiles of adjacent normal tissue samples. Because some of the samples appeared to be outliers as they contained a large number of CNPs, we suspected that they have been contaminated by tumor cells or the data had poor quality and decided to exclude them. We computed the number of CNPs for each sample as number of sites with |fCNV| > 5ε, where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
